00:10:09,409 --> 00:10:11,143
Should I say the, uh...

272
00:10:11,144 --> 00:10:12,344
- Yes.
- The giraffe? Okay.

273
00:10:12,345 --> 00:10:13,879
So...

274
00:10:13,880 --> 00:10:15,547
Hey, uh, Tim, I need you
to come with me

275
00:10:15,548 --> 00:10:16,482
for your interview.

276
00:10:16,483 --> 00:10:18,117
Okay. Good.
[INAUDIBLE]

277
00:10:18,118 --> 00:10:19,551
I guess the joke has to wait.

278
00:10:19,552 --> 00:10:20,819
Yeah. Dude, you tell it.

279
00:10:20,820 --> 00:10:21,954
- You tell it, bro.
- Well...

280
00:10:21,955 --> 00:10:23,522
No, you got it.
You got it. Say it.

281
00:10:23,523 --> 00:10:25,257
Okay, so the giraffe
is in a line...

282
00:10:25,258 --> 00:10:26,725
in a TSA line...

283
00:10:26,726 --> 00:10:27,893
- Okay.
- Waiting.

284
00:10:27,894 --> 00:10:30,863
And the...
and the agent asks him,

285
00:10:30,864 --> 00:10:32,765
"Is that your laptop?"

286
00:10:32,766 --> 00:10:40,372
And he was like,
"I thought you'd never ask."

287
00:10:40,373 --> 00:10:42,508
♪ [PERCUSSIVE BEAT] ♪

288
00:10:42,509 --> 00:10:47,413
I don't... I don't get it.

289
00:10:47,414 --> 00:10:49,348
Yeah, it's gonna take you
a while to get it.

290
00:10:49,349 --> 00:10:50,382
Okay.

291
00:10:50,383 --> 00:10:52,451
And he says, um,

292
00:10:52,452 --> 00:10:56,855
"I thought you'd never ask."

293
00:10:56,856 --> 00:10:59,825
What's the funny part?

294
00:10:59,826 --> 00:11:01,126
I don't know.
I... I found it funny.

295
00:11:01,127 --> 00:11:04,463
And it's a giraffe.
It's not a human.

296
00:11:04,464 --> 00:11:06,799
- And you thought it was funny?
- Yeah.

297
00:11:06,800 --> 00:11:08,200
What was the funny part,
though?

298
00:11:08,201 --> 00:11:09,935
Like...

299
00:11:09,936 --> 00:11:12,271
I think it was...
the funny part was the laptop,

300
00:11:12,272 --> 00:11:14,173
'cause you know how
he's so tall?

301
00:11:14,174 --> 00:11:15,507
Hmm.

302
00:11:15,508 --> 00:11:16,942
Do these subjects
really think

303
00:11:16,943 --> 00:11:18,944
my meaningless joke is funny?

304
00:11:18,945 --> 00:11:21,146
It's time to let them in
on what's really going on.

305
00:11:21,147 --> 00:11:24,516
Everyone here today
except for you is an actor.

306
00:11:24,517 --> 00:11:26,385
- Okay.
- We have all been instructed

307
00:11:26,386 --> 00:11:28,487
to laugh at that
dumb giraffe joke,

308
00:11:28,488 --> 00:11:29,888
which is not even a joke.

309
00:11:29,889 --> 00:11:32,257
It's just a meaningless thing.

310
00:11:32,258 --> 00:11:35,294
And then we see if the one
person who isn't in on it,

311
00:11:35,295 --> 00:11:36,895
which in this round was you...

312
00:11:36,896 --> 00:11:38,397
how they respond.

313
00:11:38,398 --> 00:11:40,032
Why did you never say,

314
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:41,367
"What?"

315
00:11:41,368 --> 00:11:43,902
I think it was people
laughing around me,

316
00:11:43,903 --> 00:11:46,105
and I was trying to understand
why that was funny.

317
00:11:46,106 --> 00:11:48,173
And then I had to make sense
of it in my mind,

318
00:11:48,174 --> 00:11:50,876
and then I think I made it
funny to myself.

319
00:11:50,877 --> 00:11:52,978
That process
of mental gymnastics

320
00:11:52,979 --> 00:11:55,247
is known as
cognitive dissonance.

321
00:11:55,248 --> 00:11:58,017
When you've done something
you don't truly believe in,

322
00:11:58,018 --> 00:12:00,452
like laughing just because
everyone else did,

323
00:12:00,453 --> 00:12:02,955
you'll often try to come
to terms with your behaviour

324
00:12:02,956 --> 00:12:05,124
through denial
and justification.

325
00:12:05,125 --> 00:12:07,459
It's not a joke; I just made
that up, and it's nonsense.

326
00:12:07,460 --> 00:12:09,328
I know, that's why
I thought it was funny.

327
00:12:09,329 --> 00:12:10,662
'Cause it just
made no sense?

328
00:12:10,663 --> 00:12:11,563
Yeah, that's why.

329
00:12:11,564 --> 00:12:12,965
I don't know.
That's crazy, though,

330
00:12:12,966 --> 00:12:14,466
'cause it did make me laugh.

331
00:12:14,467 --> 00:12:15,834
- [LAUGHING]
- Everyone does that.

332
00:12:15,835 --> 00:12:18,037
- Yeah.
- It's typical human behaviour...

333
00:12:18,038 --> 00:12:19,204
Yeah. It's true, though.

334
00:12:19,205 --> 00:12:21,974
...To go with the flow
and to keep things moving.

335
00:12:21,975 --> 00:12:24,443
It's about just being
a good, social person.

336
00:12:24,444 --> 00:12:27,146
It's definitely a...
a conformity thing.

337
00:12:27,147 --> 00:12:31,884
[LAUGHTER]

338
00:12:31,885 --> 00:12:36,388
One of the most disappointing
and terrifying aspects

339
00:12:36,389 --> 00:12:38,991
of our desire not to stand out

340
00:12:38,992 --> 00:12:40,993
is the bystander effect.

341
00:12:40,994 --> 00:12:44,163
People are less likely
to help victims

342
00:12:44,164 --> 00:12:46,932
if other people are around.

343
00:12:46,933 --> 00:12:49,034
One of the most famous examples

344
00:12:49,035 --> 00:12:52,304
is told in Psych 101 classes
all over the world.

345
00:12:52,305 --> 00:12:54,540
It's the story
of Kitty Genovese,

346
00:12:54,541 --> 00:12:56,542
a woman who was brutally stabbed

347
00:12:56,543 --> 00:12:58,477
and raped in New York City

348
00:12:58,478 --> 00:13:00,579
in 1964.

349
00:13:00,580 --> 00:13:02,281
It was a murder
that symbolised

350
00:13:02,282 --> 00:13:05,217
the apathy of many
to big-city crime.

351
00:13:05,218 --> 00:13:08,253
On a March night
back in 1964,

352
00:13:08,254 --> 00:13:11,023
28-year-old bar manager
Kitty Genovese

353
00:13:11,024 --> 00:13:12,925
was stabbed to death
on a street

354
00:13:12,926 --> 00:13:14,526
in Kew Gardens, Queens.

355
00:13:14,527 --> 00:13:16,395
Police say at least 38 people

356
00:13:16,396 --> 00:13:17,529
heard her screams

357
00:13:17,530 --> 00:13:19,264
but did nothing to help.

358
00:13:19,265 --> 00:13:22,568
The hypothesis was that
each and every one of them

359
00:13:22,569 --> 00:13:25,004
assumed someone else
would call the police,

360
00:13:25,005 --> 00:13:28,073
so they didn't have to bother
to do so themselves.

361
00:13:28,074 --> 00:13:29,942
It wasn't their responsibility,

362
00:13:29,943 --> 00:13:33,012
so the police were never called.

363
00:13:33,013 --> 00:13:35,948
And Kitty died.

364
00:13:35,949 --> 00:13:38,150
♪ [SOMBRE MUSIC] ♪

365
00:13:38,151 --> 00:13:39,618
But here's the thing:

366
00:13:39,619 --> 00:13:41,987
Kitty's story may
not be an example

367
00:13:41,988 --> 00:13:43,956
of conformity,

368
00:13:43,957 --> 00:13:45,991
at least not in the way
we normally think,

369
00:13:45,992 --> 00:13:50,229
because most of it
was totally untrue.

370
00:13:50,230 --> 00:13:53,632
38 people didn't
witness the attack.

371
00:13:53,633 --> 00:13:56,168
As it turns out, the actual
number of witnesses

372
00:13:56,169 --> 00:13:57,703
who could have helped and didn't

373
00:13:57,704 --> 00:14:00,439
may have been as few as two,

374
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:03,142
and people did call the police.

375
00:14:03,143 --> 00:14:07,212
Samuel Hoffman spent three
or four minutes on hold

376
00:14:07,213 --> 00:14:10,416
before finally reaching
a police dispatcher.

377
00:14:10,417 --> 00:14:13,585
So where did
the number 38 come from?

378
00:14:13,586 --> 00:14:16,088
It's theorised
that the police commissioner

379
00:14:16,089 --> 00:14:17,956
actually lied to a reporter

380
00:14:17,957 --> 00:14:20,192
about the number of witnesses
who did nothing

381
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:23,195
in order to cover up why
the police took so long

382
00:14:23,196 --> 00:14:25,230
to arrive at the scene
of the crime.

383
00:14:25,231 --> 00:14:28,300
And the narrative
of uncaring New Yorkers

384
00:14:28,301 --> 00:14:30,636
turning a blind eye
to a woman's murder

385
00:14:30,637 --> 00:14:32,237
spread around the world,

386
00:14:32,238 --> 00:14:34,273
making front page headlines.

387
00:14:34,274 --> 00:14:36,375
As more and more sources

388
00:14:36,376 --> 00:14:38,377
repeated reports they'd heard,

389
00:14:38,378 --> 00:14:41,313
rather than going back
to investigate the truth,

390
00:14:41,314 --> 00:14:43,082
a psychological phenomenon

391
00:14:43,083 --> 00:14:46,452
known as information cascade
took place.

392
00:14:46,453 --> 00:14:49,121
An information cascade develops

393
00:14:49,122 --> 00:14:51,390
when people have
little information themselves,

394
00:14:51,391 --> 00:14:53,525
so they depend on inferences
they can make

395
00:14:53,526 --> 00:14:56,228
based on earlier
people's actions.

396
00:14:56,229 --> 00:15:00,099
So the conformity wasn't on
the part of the eyewitnesses.

397
00:15:00,100 --> 00:15:03,268
It was in the reporting
of the story.

398
00:15:03,269 --> 00:15:05,137
There's a saying in journalism:

399
00:15:05,138 --> 00:15:14,146
"Some stories are
too good to check."

400
00:15:14,147 --> 00:15:16,148
[PROJECTOR WHIRRING]

401
00:15:16,149 --> 00:15:18,183
I'm going to give you
this cup

402
00:15:18,184 --> 00:15:21,120
that contains lysergic acid...

403
00:15:21,121 --> 00:15:23,355
100 micrograms.

404
00:15:23,356 --> 00:15:25,224
Clinical trials:

405
00:15:25,225 --> 00:15:27,626
they can be enlightening,

406
00:15:27,627 --> 00:15:28,627
frightening,

407
00:15:28,628 --> 00:15:30,095
dangerous...

408
00:15:30,096 --> 00:15:32,131
It seems to want to take me
over too much, you see,

409
00:15:32,132 --> 00:15:33,632
and I don't want
to let myself go.

410
00:15:33,633 --> 00:15:36,201
And also the perfect
high-stakes setting

411
00:15:36,202 --> 00:15:41,373
to test the power
of conformity.

412
00:15:41,374 --> 00:15:46,578
♪ [TENSE MUSIC] ♪

413
00:15:46,579 --> 00:15:49,381
This is Emma.

414
00:15:49,382 --> 00:15:51,116
She thinks she's taking part

415
00:15:51,117 --> 00:15:52,251
in a group study

416
00:15:52,252 --> 00:15:53,519
to measure the side effects

417
00:15:53,520 --> 00:15:57,122
of a new hallucinogenic drug.

418
00:15:57,123 --> 00:15:59,491
So the drug that you are
helping us research today

419
00:15:59,492 --> 00:16:02,294
is NC-47.

420
00:16:02,295 --> 00:16:04,697
Today we're investigating
possible side effects.

421
00:16:04,698 --> 00:16:08,200
You know, there've been some
audio-visual distortions.

422
00:16:08,201 --> 00:16:11,370
You may see some images
behind your eyes...

423
00:16:11,371 --> 00:16:15,207
um, you know, some general
feelings of either calmness

424
00:16:15,208 --> 00:16:16,642
or euphoria.

425
00:16:16,643 --> 00:16:18,510
We're trying to examine those
a little further

426
00:16:18,511 --> 00:16:20,446
and find out a little bit
more about how

427
00:16:20,447 --> 00:16:22,681
this drug is affecting
everybody.

428
00:16:22,682 --> 00:16:24,783
Emma is already looking
to the rest of the group

429
00:16:24,784 --> 00:16:26,051
for comfort.

430
00:16:26,052 --> 00:16:27,786
Just take a cup,
and just hang onto it.

431
00:16:27,787 --> 00:16:29,555
[WHISPERING] Okay.

432
00:16:29,556 --> 00:16:31,557
If everyone else is
participating willingly,

433
00:16:31,558 --> 00:16:34,493
it must be okay for her, too.

434
00:16:34,494 --> 00:16:35,728
[LAUGHTER]

435
00:16:35,729 --> 00:16:37,363
We're all, like,
scared to death.

436
00:16:37,364 --> 00:16:39,131
Okay.

437
00:16:39,132 --> 00:16:41,367
Go.

438
00:16:41,368 --> 00:16:45,838
♪ [ELECTRONIC MUSIC] ♪

439
00:16:45,839 --> 00:16:47,740
But here's the catch:

440
00:16:47,741 --> 00:16:50,743
our subject didn't take
a hallucinogenic drug at all.

441
00:16:50,744 --> 00:16:53,512
It was simply a shot
of flavoured water.

442
00:16:53,513 --> 00:16:57,282
Just relax and concentrate.

443
00:16:57,283 --> 00:16:58,884
We'll give this just
a little bit of time

444
00:16:58,885 --> 00:17:00,319
to set in.

445
00:17:00,320 --> 00:17:02,621
It doesn't take long
for our actors to feel

446
00:17:02,622 --> 00:17:05,691
the supposed side effects
of the so-called drug.

447
00:17:05,692 --> 00:17:07,259
It's like a...

448
00:17:07,260 --> 00:17:09,228
like a line that goes across.

449
00:17:09,229 --> 00:17:11,530
It's almost like I'm looking
through a kaleidoscope,

450
00:17:11,531 --> 00:17:12,765
but it's, like, fuzzy.

451
00:17:12,766 --> 00:17:15,434
Will our test subject
go along with the group?

452
00:17:15,435 --> 00:17:17,603
Or will she be bold enough
to stand out

453
00:17:17,604 --> 00:17:19,238
and say the truth?

454
00:17:19,239 --> 00:17:22,441
It's like a... like a lava lamp
sort of thing.

455
00:17:22,442 --> 00:17:24,209
Hmm.

456
00:17:24,210 --> 00:17:25,411
Emma?

457
00:17:25,412 --> 00:17:26,612
Um, I honestly...

458
00:17:26,613 --> 00:17:28,247
I don't see anything.
[LAUGHS]

459
00:17:28,248 --> 00:17:30,215
- Mm.
- I don't see any shadows,

460
00:17:30,216 --> 00:17:31,684
shapes...

461
00:17:31,685 --> 00:17:33,552
I'm like, "Come on,
I want to see a shape."

462
00:17:33,553 --> 00:17:35,287
But I don't see anything, no.

463
00:17:35,288 --> 00:17:38,490
Emma's honesty is making her
an outsider.

464
00:17:38,491 --> 00:17:41,760
Notice how she says she wants
to feel the side effects,

465
00:17:41,761 --> 00:17:44,830
which would enable her
to fit in with the group.

466
00:17:44,831 --> 00:17:48,334
You can all sit down again.

467
00:17:48,335 --> 00:17:50,469
Okay, I want to do
the audio test.

468
00:17:50,470 --> 00:17:51,837
We're just gonna
go down the line,

469
00:17:51,838 --> 00:17:54,506
and I want you to just
say the word "hello."

470
00:17:54,507 --> 00:17:57,576
Here's another opportunity
for Emma to conform.

471
00:17:57,577 --> 00:17:59,378
Will she go along
with the group

472
00:17:59,379 --> 00:18:02,214
when she sees the actors
pretend to experience

473
00:18:02,215 --> 00:18:05,718
an auditory reaction
to the alleged drug?

474
00:18:05,719 --> 00:18:07,553
Hello.

475
00:18:07,554 --> 00:18:08,554
Louder.

476
00:18:08,555 --> 00:18:10,889
Um, hello!

477
00:18:10,890 --> 00:18:12,725
And how did that feel?
What's your reaction?

478
00:18:12,726 --> 00:18:13,759
I hear, like, a delay.

479
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:15,027
Like, um...

480
00:18:15,028 --> 00:18:16,562
Yeah, it could be
called an echo.

481
00:18:16,563 --> 00:18:17,830
- It's more like a...
- Mm-hmm.

482
00:18:17,831 --> 00:18:19,798
Like a reverb or something.

483
00:18:19,799 --> 00:18:21,333
Yup, that's very common.

484
00:18:21,334 --> 00:18:23,135
All right, Ivory.

485
00:18:23,136 --> 00:18:25,804
Hello.

